<DOC><DOCNO> AP880721-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0601EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-China-Typhoon 1stLd-Writethru a0475 07-21 0447</FIRST><SECOND>PM-China-Typhoon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0459</SECOND><HEAD>Typhoon Kills Six, Causes Extensive Damage</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details. No pickup</NOTE><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A typhoon that slammed into the southern city ofShantou killed at least six people and caused millions of dollarsin damage to ships, homes, power lines and rice paddies, officialssaid today.   Typhoon Warren hit Shantou and neighboring counties in coastalGuangdong province on Tuesday night with 80 mph winds andtorrential rains before dissipating inland.   The overseas edition of the People's Daily today reported sixdeaths and 70 people injured in the Shantou municipal district.   But the China News Service said 106 were injured. It said totaldamage from the storm was estimated at $160 million.   Li Lieqin of the Shantou Foreign Affairs Office said bytelephone that six of the injured were hit when a wall toppled overat a chemical plant. He said one person was in serious condition.   China News said the typhoon washed away 147 hydraulic projects,toppled more than 4,000 houses and 14,300 huts and damaged 38,000other houses during its 16-hour strike. It said more than 432,000acres of crops were damaged.   The People's Daily estimated the damage to rice paddies at $9.5million and said $6 million worth of fruit trees were uprooted. Lisaid there was heavy damage in particular to the region's orangeand banana crops.   The news service said the typhoon damaged telephonecommunications, knocked down four bridges, smashed more than 30miles of roads and destroyed nearly 200 ships, seven of which sank.   The People's Daily said hundreds of electric poles were knockeddown and more than 19 miles of river embankments and 16 miles ofsee levees washed out. Li said four bridges in the Shantou areawere destroyed but did not say how big they were.   The city's electricity and telephone service were restored todayafter a 24-hour outage.   Guangdong provincial officials said there were no deaths orextensive damage in Canton, a city of more than 2 million about 190miles southwest of Shantou.   Details of cleanup operations were not disclosed. Li said armedpolice were called in before the typhoon hit to take protectivemeasures at the Shantou oil depot, and the air force battened downthe city airport.   Peasants in the area, warned of the coming storm, labored theday before the typhoon hit to bring in grain, but Li said earlyestimates showed 55,000 tons were lost.   Southeastern China was battered by heavy rains and flooding inMay and June. Official reports said five people were killed and 370injured in Guangdong and at least 171 were killed in neighboringprovinces in those storms.</TEXT></DOC>